20. navus Bentley prints gnavus, which has however but little support srom the MSS. From Cicero's words (Orat. 47, 158) not-ierant, et navi et nari, quihus cum in praeponi oporteret, dulcius visum esl ignoti ignavi ignari dicare quam ut veritas postulabat, it might seem that the forms with g were unknown to him. But gnavus is often found in good Ciceronian MSS. and is admitted by the best editors (eg. Halm in de Imp. Pomp. 7, 18): nurus seems nowhere to occur, nor is gnotus actually found except in the grammarians. It is very doubtful whether gnavus is from the same root as gnarus, the meaning being entirely different <Corssen Ι. 83): but cp. Curt. Gr. 21. dotalibus coming to him through his wife, and therefore not due either to inherstance, or to his own energy and business skill. emetat, only found here.

22. Mutus, probably the name of a real person, known to Horace’s readers. Orelli remarks that Horace, though often borrowing his types of character from Lucilius, does not limit himself to them. Mutus is found as a cognomen on an inscrip- tion, quoted by Bentley, who restored the true reading for the vulgate, Illucz'us, z'ndzgnum.
